      "explanation": "The data show methylmercury concentrations increasing by approximately a factor of 10 at each successive trophic level (0.0002 → 0.002 → 0.04 → 1.6 ppm), a hallmark pattern of biomagnification - the process by which persistent, fat-soluble pollutants become increasingly concentrated as they move up the food chain because each predator must consume large quantities of prey, accumulating the pollutant faster than it can be excreted. Since the fishing community eats top-level predatory fish, they are exposed to the highest concentrations and face the greatest risk. Choice B confuses biomagnification (across the food chain) with bioaccumulation (within a single organism) and incorrectly attributes the increase to water consumption. Choice C incorrectly links eutrophication - a nutrient enrichment process - to heavy metal uptake; these are unrelated mechanisms. Choice D is a trap using a fabricated threshold value; the U.S. EPA action level for methylmercury in fish is approximately 1.0 ppm, meaning the 1.6 ppm level in predatory fish does represent a significant health concern.",
