      "id": "pt_enviro_p1_frq_003",
      "frqType": "regular",
      "isCalc": false,
      "title": "Energy Resources, Air Pollution, and Environmental Justice",
      "prompt": "Coal-fired power plants have historically been the dominant source of electricity in many regions of the United States. While coal provides a relatively inexpensive and reliable source of energy, its combustion produces a variety of air pollutants including sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen oxides (NOx), particulate matter (PM2.5), mercury (Hg), and carbon dioxide (CO2). Studies have consistently shown that coal-fired power plants are disproportionately located near low-income communities and communities of color, raising significant environmental justice concerns.\n\nA state government is considering a proposal to close an aging coal-fired power plant located on the edge of a low-income urban neighborhood and replace it with a combination of natural gas and solar photovoltaic (PV) energy. Community members, energy companies, and environmental groups all have perspectives on this proposal.\n\nUse your knowledge of environmental science to answer the following questions.",
